We recommended that in compliance with Chapter 7 – Supplies and Properties of the MNGAS for LGUs Volume I, the Local Chief Executive to:
Create an Inventory Committee to conduct a physical count of unissued inventory items by type at least once a year and prepare the RPCI to be submitted to the Office of the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year;
Instruct all Department Heads responsible for the custody of inventory items to prepare a Requisition and Issuance Slip (RIS) for all inventory issuances. This will ensure proper monitoring and accountability, and the RIS should be submitted to the General Services Office (GSO;
Direct the GSO to prepare the weekly Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) based on the original RIS submitted by the various offices holding inventory custody. The SSMI should be submitted to the City Accountant for proper recognition of supplies and materials expenses; and
Instruct the City Accountant and the GSO to maintain updated Supplies Ledger Cards and stock cards, respectively.

2.13	We recommended that the City Mayor instruct:
The City Engineer to provide the City Accountant with copies of Certificate of Completion as the basis for reclassifying completed projects from CIP accounts to appropriate PPE accounts;
The City Accountant to draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to reclassify costs of completed projects to the appropriate asset accounts based on Certificates of Completion and to record the necessary depreciation attributed to these completed projects;
The City Accountant to review the transactions recorded under the CIP accounts and prepare the required CIPLC for each project to ensure proper monitoring of projects in progress; and
The City Engineer and City Accountant to exert more effort to identify generic and/or unidentified projects recorded under the CIP accounts to ensure their actual existence and fair presentation of the financial statements.

4.12	To promote better control over inventories and reflect an accurate and more reliable balances of Inventory accounts in the Financial Statements, we recommended that Management:
Create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of unissued inventory items by type at least once a year and prepare the RPCI to be submitted to the Office of the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year;
Instruct all Department Heads responsible for the custody of the inventory items to prepare RIS for all the issuances of inventories for proper monitoring and accountability and submit the same to the GSO;
Instruct the GSO to prepare the weekly SSMI based on the original RIS submitted by the various offices responsible in the custody of these inventories and submit the same to the City Accountant for proper recognition of supplies and materials expenses; and
Instruct the City Accountant and the GSO to maintain an updated Supplies Ledger Cards and stock cards, respectively.

Instruct Human Resource Management Officer (HRMO) to assess its existing organizational structure and include the number of JO personnel needed to comply with the service requirements of the City in its Organizational Structure and Staffing Pattern plan to avoid excessive hiring of JOs;

b. Instruct the HRMO to develop written policies or manual on hiring contract of services and job orders that will serve as a guide and basis for engaging the services of JOs in order to promote the best practices in the management thereof.

c. Require all JO personnel to enroll in the biometric system of the City to ensure compliance with the required number of hours of work in order to avoid payment of unrendered services.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that:

the Inventory Committee immediately conduct a complete physical inventory of all Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE) of the City,  prepare and submit a reliable RPCPPE thereon; 

the City Accountant and the General Service Officer regularly coordinate to facilitate the reconciliation of the difference noted between the physical inventory report and the general ledger balance of each PPE account;  

the City Accountant make appropriate adjustments to reflect the correct balances of each PPE Account maintained in the General Ledger as well as in the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment; and

create Disposal Committee to immediately undertake the disposal of all unserviceable properties and other unusable supplies following the provisions of Section 79 of PD 1445, to avoid further deterioration and earn higher proceeds from their sale and thereby, relieve the custodians of their responsibility/accountability and free some space in the store room for more productive and worthwhile purposes.

We recommended that:

the City Treasurer  furnish the City Accountant a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year as basis for recording the Real Property Tax/Special Education Tax Receivable, to establish a more accurate and reliable amount on said accounts;

the Local Chief Executive instruct the City Treasurer to intensify collection efforts and tap the services of the City Legal Officer in the collection of taxes due and collectible by sending Notice of Delinquency to RPT Taxpayers; 

form a committee to conduct an information dissemination regarding the importance of paying taxes promptly and the consequences of non-payment of taxes; and

review the collection strategy in place if any, and enhance its operating effectiveness in order to improve the collection efficiency of the City.

We recommended that the Management:

a)	strictly observe City Ordinance No. 1602-96 on the grant of Scholarship Program of the City Government. The Scholarship Committee may recommend to the Sangguniang Panglungsod the amendment of certain provisions of the Scholarship Ordinance in order to improve the delivery of public service to the poor but deserving students in the City of Dagupan;

b)	strictly enforce the scholarship guidelines adopted by the City Government in relation to the selection of applicants so as not to jeopardize the objective of scholarship program, in particular the determination of their economic status and the evaluation of  grades;

c)	require the remaining scholars enrolled in UPANG-PHINMA and other universities and colleges to submit their grades and conduct evaluation to determine those students with failing grades;

d)	inform the thirty three (33) scholars that their scholarship for School Year 2019-2020   would be discontinued due to the reasons discussed above; and

e)	discontinue the scholarship program given to the seventeen (17) disqualified students.

